Johnny Rocket says:
            
           
            
            			October 1st, 2016 at 11:19 am  
Stay away.  If their offering was a good deal, it would have been
snapped up by institutional investors.  And how can they “guarantee”
a 7% return in a 0.5% world?  And you need to think about why anyone
would risk their money buying real estate from a radio commercial or
website.  Also, it takes up to three months or longer to have your money returned if you decide to sell.  And they are NOT a public REIT
(regardless of what they tell you).  They are “public” to the extent
they are registered with the SEC so the public can view their offering,
but they DO NOT trade on the open market such as any legitimate
REIT would…XLRE and many others.  If you are a novice investor, I suggest you contact a Certified Financial Planner (CFP) who is also
a Fiduciary (which means they are in business to serve you and not
their best interests).  They can review this with you and I am certain they will tell you essentially what I have written.  You MUST complete
your due diligence before making any decision like this.
  Good luck.
REPLYDouglas J. Lewis, CFP says:October 26th, 2016 at 5:54 pmYou are correct.  The non-traded REITs are public but not traded on stock exchanges.  There are Private REITs also which are not traded on stock exchanges.  The fact that this one is public tells you the reporting to the SEC is required. As far as safety, the public REITs are safer than the private REITs. However, there is another risk in the traded, public REITs that the non-traded ones avoid.  This is the daily potential drop in the value of your investment. The value of your non-traded REIT is not subject to marketability. Also, do not confuse the income, your monthly distribution from your REIT with your return.  You should be interested in knowing how much is your monthly income going to be (although not guaranteed), how long your income period will be (how many years), and when will there be a liquidity event.  This liquidity event is the most crucial.  During the operational period  of your REIT you are receiving a percentage return ON your investment.  Then at liquidity, you will find out what percentage receive OF your investment. If you receive 100% return upon liquidity! this turned out to be a good investment.  There are some excellent non-traded REITs and some lousy ones.  The prospectus is the best way to understand the risks.  As a  Certified Financial Planner, I always begin my due diligence here.  Then I go a lot further utilizing other due diligence attorney firms to get their written evaluations.  So far, the biggest risk I see with this risk is the lack of any information on a liquidity event.  Other risks I have found are with regard to the sponsors.



