Ray Wirta
Chairman of the Board
Director Since August 1997
Chairman of the Board Chairman of the Board
Mr. Wirta has been the Independent Chair of our Board since May 2014 and was previously the Vice Chair of our Board from November 2013 to May 2014. He has served as the President of the Investment Properties Group at the Irvine Company since June 2010 and as Chief Executive Officer of The Koll Company since November 2009. Mr. Wirta served as our Chief Executive Officer from September 2001 to June 2005, and Chief Executive Officer of our predecessor company, CBRE Services, Inc., from May 1999 to September 2001. He also served as Chief Operating Officer of that predecessor company from May 1998 to May 1999. Mr. Wirta served as a director and Non-Executive Chairman of Realty Finance Corporation, where he was the Chairman from May 2005 through August 2009. He also served as Interim Chief Executive Officer and President of that company from April 2007 to September 2007. 
https://tic-irvinecompany-stage.sitewire.net/ray-wirta
Ray Wirta is President of the Irvine Company’s Investment Properties Group (“IPG”).  In this role, he serves on the Company’s Office of the Chairman management committee that also includes Chairman Donald Bren and ICCD President Dan Young.
As IPG President, Mr. Wirta guides all aspects of the company’s office, retail and resort properties in Orange County, Los Angeles, San Diego, Silicon Valley and Chicago, including development, marketing and management.
IPG’s high-quality portfolio includes 500 office properties, 41 retail centers, five yacht marinas, three golf courses and three hotels, including the world-class Resort at Pelican Hill® in Newport Coast®.
In addition, Mr. Wirta oversees Irvine Company’s corporate functional groups: Corporate Communications, Legal & Risk Management, Financial Services, Corporate Marketing, Information Technology and Human Resources.
Mr. Wirta is a respected real estate executive.  From 1997 to 2005, he served as Chief Executive Officer of CB Richard Ellis and continues to serve as Vice Chairman and Director for the firm.  He served as President of The Koll Company from 1981 to 1997; as Senior Vice President of World Savings from 1979 to 1981; and as President of Continental Service Company (a Bank of America subsidiary) from 1973 to 1979.
Mr. Wirta received a bachelor’s degree in Economics from Long Beach State College and an MBA in International Management from Golden Gate University.



Never Never Never says:
            
           
            
            			August 20th, 2016 at 6:58 pm  
For anyone thinking to invest here, you must complete your due
diligence first.  Read all the negative reviews and then ask yourself, if this is such a great deal, why are the negatives so numerous?  The
answer is that this is not a low risk enterprise, there are no legal
protections for you, there is no governmental oversight or review to ensure adherence to industry and fiduciary standards.  In addition, as
one commenter stated, it took three months to sell his investment and
receive the funds.  If you invest, do so with a PUBLIC REIT (which RU
is NOT despite the owners comments).  You can buy a public REIT on
Monday, decide its not for you and sell on Tuesday and have the funds
in your account by Friday or early the following week.  Since RU is
a NON traded REIT, you must go through them to find a buyer and who
knows how long that could take.  And you do not know, at any given time, the value of your shares since this is a private business and
not subject to the same rules as a PULLIC REIT.  You must be certain
you fully understand exactly what the risks are and decide if they justify lending them your money.  And remember, a PUBLIC REIT is traded in the public stock market just like any other stock and RU IS NOT TRADED.  That alone is a giant red flag that something is very wrong here. Caveat Emptor.
REPLYUChgo MBA, Yale JD says:August 26th, 2016 at 11:47 amNever Never is correct.  The reason real estate is such a good investment is because of a very large non-cash deduction — depreciation — that serves to reduce the TAXABLE income from the rents.  In other words, real estate has two types of income (broadly speaking): taxable income — the rents and similar cash flows in excess of deductions — and nontaxable cashflow — from depreciation.
The investors are only paid out of the taxable income which may be a quite small portion of total cashflow.  The promoters keep the rest!!
Potentially (depending on how much cash the offering receives) the promoters may buy real estate for 100% cash (all from the investors) but receive nearly all of the cashflow.
Another twist on that approach would be for the promoters to take a mortgage on the already purchased real estate and pay those cash proceeds to themselves.  None would be required to be paid to the investors because mortgage proceeds are not taxable income.
As Never Never points out owning a NON-public REIT is kind of like owning a timeshare at a resort.  You might not be able to sell it.




