Rating

   
Joe says:
            
           
            
            			August 12th, 2016 at 1:09 pm  
Full Disclosure: I have not yet invested, but am currently researching this as a way to diversify my investments in 401(K), Roth IRA, stock brokerage account, 529 plan and home equity.
The research I have done (I am a Finance professional with a degree in Finance and an MBA) is all positive thus far. This is a legit opportunity with the same risks as any other investment…what you need to determine is whether or not the risk is worth the potential return of ~6.5%. 
I must say that the negative reviews on this site seem to be coming from uneducated people who blindly invested or know little about REITs and/or public exchanges. This REIT is subject to SEC regulation, but is done so under relatively new laws pertaining to crowd-funding. In other words, the SEC wanted individuals to be able to invest in opportunities without having to go through institutional investors or brokerage firms. This is a good thing for the individual. It DOESN’T make it a ponzi scheme. The SEC is in fact regulating this REIT, which doesn’t eliminate risk, but does ensure it is NOT a “scam”.
To the point about risk, your risk here is that the economy tanks or the commercial real estate market crashes (unlikely, but more realistic given recent history). The value of the properties in the REIT would decline, your share value would decline, and the company may not be able to repurchase your shares if you wanted to “cash out”. You have these same exact risks when investing in the stock market. If you put $500 in a DOW Jones index fund in 2007 and wanted to cash out in 2009, you would only get back 33% of what you put in, and you wouldn’t have received a dividend. If you bought Citigroup stock in 2007 @ $55, it was worth less than a dollar in 2009. Stock prices (even for safe companies) go up and down based on nothing but market speculation. At least the value of this REIT is tied to real property. The only added risk of this REIT is that the market for share repurchase is completely with the fund. They don’t have to buy back your shares, but if they don’t, their fund would fail. 
Last comment: anyone who would blindly dump $80K (or any amount) into anything without testing it first is not worthy of providing their opinion. Start with $500, see how it returns, then build it up slowly if you are happy. Get rich quick doesn’t align with safe investment.
REPLYMrMatterOfFact says:August 30th, 2016 at 9:12 pmIf you have to say “this isn’t a get rich quick scheme”, it’s a get rich quick scheme.
Rich Uncles says:August 18th, 2016 at 7:07 pmWe love sophisticated investors.  Google Ray Wirta – this is your new real estate partner.  This isn’t a get rich quick scheme, but is a prudent way to own a portfolio of income producing real estate, with a 50% debt, with creditworthy tenants who pay all property related expenses.




