With New REIT, You Don't Need a Rich Uncle to Invest in Commercial Real Estate
Wirta, Hofer Launching Latest REIT with a Goal of Shearing Investment Fees for Small Investors
By Mark Heschmeyer
July 21, 2015





Email



Print










Former CB Richard Ellis CEO and vice chairman Ray Wirta, and real estate industry veteran Harold Hofer, who have a long history of championing small-dollar-investor access to big-dollar commercial real estate, are looking to offer shares in their latest REIT, Rich Uncles REIT Inc.,  with the goal of raising up to $1 billion for the non-exchange listed public REIT. Wirta and Hofer are playing up the small-investor component of Rich Uncles REIT in hopes of making more of the investment by mom-and-pop investors go towards real estate and less to financial intermediaries. They've set up Rich Uncles as an alternate, internet-based distribution channel to sell shares that excludes payment of commissions and expense reimbursements to advisory intermediaries. Typically, the sponsor of a non-exchange listed public REIT, such as Rich Uncles, enlists the sales expertise of an in-house dealer-manager responsible for marketing shares in a REIT. In compensation, the broker-dealer or financial intermediary usually receives up to 10% of investments made in the REIT as commissions or cost reimbursements. In fashioning an alternative funding scheme, Rich Uncles believes its real estate investment vehicle delivers roughly 10% more of the investment amount to acquire the actual real estate, rather than in the form of commissions and reimbursements. The REIT expects to use a substantial amount of the net proceeds from the upcoming public offering to invest in single-tenant income-producing corporate properties. Hofer and Wirta have a history of trying to open up CRE deals to smaller investors. The pair previously sponsored two REITs: Nexregen Firewheel Real Estate Investment Trust in 2007, a single-asset REIT that offered to invest in a limited partnership that owned a shopping center in Garland, TX.  More recently, the pair organized Rich Uncles Real Estate Investment Trust I in 2012 to invest in single-tenant properties in California. Both offerings used Wirta’s and Hofer’s proprietary web-based system that pools small-dollar interests made by individual investors to buy commercial properties. 

GET IN TOUCH        Contact CoStar News Team:   News@CoStar.com 

